A touch probe is a device used to measure the distance or position of an object by means of touch. It typically consists of a flexible probe with a sharp tip that is deflected by the force of contact with the object. The distance between the probe and the object can then be measured using a sensitive force sensor, which converts the deflection of the probe into an electrical signal. This signal can then be processed by a computer to determine the distance or position of the object.

Touch probes are used in a variety of applications, including robotics, manufacturing, and medical imaging. In robotics, touch probes are used to sense the position of objects and to navigate through cluttered environments. In manufacturing, touch probes are used to measure the position of parts on a production line, ensuring that they are positioned accurately. In medical imaging, touch probes are used to measure the position of tumors or other abnormalities, helping doctors to diagnose and treat diseases.

Overall, touch probes are an important tool for measuring distance and position, and they are used in a variety of applications to improve accuracy and efficiency.
